# Fixed R code for calculating Lyapunov exponents on Google stock data
# Using existing df_googl$Open vector

# Install and load required package if not already installed
if (!require("nonlinearTseries")) {
  install.packages("nonlinearTseries")
  library(nonlinearTseries)
}

# Calculate Lyapunov exponent directly from the df_googl$Open data
calculate_simple_lyapunov <- function(prices, embedding_dim = 3, time_delay = 1) {
  # Convert prices to returns (percentage changes)
  returns <- diff(log(prices)) * 100
  
  # Remove any NA values
  returns <- returns[!is.na(returns)]
  
  # Create time series object
  ts_returns <- ts(returns)
  
  # Calculate Lyapunov exponent with radius parameter
  # The radius parameter determines the size of the neighborhood to be considered
  # Setting it to NULL makes the function estimate it automatically based on the data
  lyap_result <- maxLyapunov(time.series = ts_returns, 
                            min.embedding.dim = embedding_dim, 
                            max.embedding.dim = embedding_dim,
                            time.lag = time_delay,
                            radius = NULL,  # This will estimate the radius automatically
                            do.plot = TRUE)
  
  # Extract Lyapunov exponent
  lyap_exp <- mean(lyap_result$lyapunov)
  
  # Print results
  cat("Lyapunov Exponent:", lyap_exp, "\n")
  
  if (lyap_exp > 0) {
    cat("Interpretation: Chaotic behavior detected in the stock price movements.\n")
  } else if (lyap_exp < 0) {
    cat("Interpretation: The system is converging to a stable state.\n")
  } else {
    cat("Interpretation: The system is in a steady state.\n")
  }
  
  return(lyap_result)
}

# One-line usage with your existing data
lyap_result <- calculate_simple_lyapunov(df_googl$Open)
